<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1436,1906,2002]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1906,1930]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Etymology:</emphasis>
From the Latin adjective 
<emphasis box="[639,768,1906,1930]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">decapitatus</emphasis>
, meaning without head, by reference to the decollation of upper whorls in all available specimens, no doubt as a result of dissolution by deep-sea bottom water below the aragonitic compensation depth.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1436,151,248]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,317,152,176]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Remarks:</emphasis>
The 
<specimenCount box="[375,531,152,176]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="generic" typeStatus="paratypes">two paratypes</specimenCount>
are similar in all respects to the 
<typeStatus box="[898,999,151,175]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">holotype</typeStatus>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kantor &amp; Puillandre &amp; Rivasseau &amp; Bouchet" authorityYear="2012" box="[1010,1247,152,176]" class="Gastropoda" family="Belomitridae" genus="Belomitra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="decapitata">
<emphasis box="[1010,1247,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Belomitra decapitata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is rather distinct in the combination of shape with numerous, well pronounced axial ribs, and the thin and fragile shell. It has some resemblance to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kantor &amp; Puillandre &amp; Rivasseau &amp; Bouchet" authorityYear="2012" box="[326,526,224,248]" class="Gastropoda" family="Belomitridae" genus="Belomitra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="admete">
<emphasis box="[326,526,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Belomitra admete</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the differences are discussed in the Remarks section of that species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
